            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#VM #JP">
                <ab>
                   <lb n="1"/><supplied reason="explanation">ἐ</supplied>νταῦθα κῖται ὁ
                    <lb n="2"/><unclear>μ</unclear>ακαρίας μνήμης
                    <lb n="3"/><supplied reason="lost">Ἀ</supplied><unclear>γ</unclear>άθων χρηστὸς <expan><abbr>κ</abbr><ex>αὶ</ex></expan>
                    <lb n="4"/><supplied reason="lost">ἄ</supplied>μενπτος διελθῶν
                    <lb n="5"/><supplied reason="lost">τὸ</supplied>ν βίον ἀπετέθη τῇ
                    <lb n="6"/><supplied reason="lost">πρ</supplied>ὸ <num value="13">ιγ</num> <expan><abbr>καλ<am><g ref="#sinusoid">𐆌</g></am></abbr><ex>ανδῶν</ex></expan> ἀπριλιων
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app>
                        <note>Text after Orsi 1895</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="3-4"><note>Orsi: κ-/[ὲ]; Agnello: κ(αὶ)</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Qui giace Agatone di beata memoria, buono ed irreprensibile: arrivato al termine della vita, fu deposto il 20 marzo [trans. Agnello]</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--epitaph of Agathon; Agnello follows Ferrua in noting that the chrestos kai amemptos formula is usually pagan, and that when it passes into Christian epig., as here, it is usually altered in its form, as with dielthon ton bion here.--></p>
            </div>
